# Finding your place

Move-in day marks the beginning of a huge transition for most incoming students. New surroundings, classes, and an entirely new community can breed stress and feelings of unfamiliarity.

When I moved in this fall, I had no idea what to expect. Just as I had finished unpacking my last box, within a couple of hours I found myself strolling into the Stevenson event center for Slugpalooza. This was my first time at an event on campus and honestly, it sparked the beginning of my involvement in what the University of California Santa Cruz (UCSC) has to offer.  

There are many connecting events during the first six weeks of school, also known as [slug start](https://news.ucsc.edu/2025/09/slug-start-2025/). During these six weeks, the college hosts activities with the intention of bringing people in the community together through fun activities. Slug start is designed to help maximize student’s ability to find their place.   

UCSC doesn’t just throw you into college and expect you to figure it out alone. Slug start  immediately fills the calendar with mixers, concerts, resource fairs, job fairs, and traditions like [Cornucopia](https://events.ucsc.edu/event/cornucopia-2025/?utm_campaign=widget&utm_medium=widget&utm_source=Events+at+UC+Santa+Cruz) which is one of the earliest and biggest campus events. Cornucopia takes over the entirety of the east field for around four hours. Essentially a club fair, hundreds of clubs, sports teams, fraternities, sororities, and campus resources, all gather in one place making it really easy to discover what UCSC has to offer and what interests you. Cornucopia can feel a bit overwhelming with tables everywhere, people trying to get my attention and more sign-up sheets than I could have imagined. Nevertheless, it still became the best introduction to college, better than I could have ever imagined.   

Slug start and Cornucopia gave me immediate ways to get engaged with UCSC’s club scene and made the transition to college a bit less overwhelming and far less intimidating. By showing up to these events, I began to find where I belong and fit in, finding like minded people every step of the way. During cornucopia every organization is in one place at once. This is important because I was able to talk directly with active members of the club which also helped me get a full picture of what I’m signing up for.

The in personness and approachability that cornucopia provides is what makes it so special, in a way that scrolling online fails to imitate. To make your your incoming experience more pleasant, I came up with three quick pieces of advice to remember before heading into Cornucopia: 

1) Give yourself enough time to approach any booth that looks interesting to you; you can always narrow things down later.  
2) Don’t limit yourself to one club or interest to partake in, start wide.  
3) Pay attention to time commitments. An extracurricular should add meaning to your schedule, not stress.

Even if you miss cornucopia getting involved is extremely easy via the ["Get Involved at UCSC"](https://getinvolved.ucsc.edu/student-organizations/join/) page on the UCSC website. There are also other ways to get involved through apps like [SlugSync](https://getinvolved.ucsc.edu/student-organizations/join/), which helps students “stay engaged, discover new communities, and make the most of campus life.” Clubs also use Instagram accounts in various ways to share events, news, and what they do. [Pupcycled](https://www.pupcycled.org/), an organization that turns donated belongings into dog toys, uses their   [Instagram Account](https://www.instagram.com/pupcycledtoys/) to announce toy making events, the need for volunteers, and document what their club is all about. Many clubs operate similarly to this. A club I'm in, [challenge](https://challengeucsc.com/), also uses their [Instagram account](https://www.instagram.com/challengeucsc/?hl=en) for the same thing and through the club I felt like I have found my place and people, making me feel welcomed.  

Starting college can be exciting and confusing while also overwhelming. If there is one takeaway I could draw from my first weeks at UCSC, it’s that getting involved is not as scary as it seems. The university gives you everything you need to have a strong start and in turn, you just need to show up, explore, and talk to people. For any student searching for community or a new hobby, UCSC’s club scene is one of the best places to begin.
